{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}} {{Infobox galaxy cluster | name = Abell 222 | image = | caption = | credit = | epoch = [[J2000]] | constellation = [[Cetus]] | ra = {{RA|01|37|27.4}}<ref name=SIMBAD>{{cite simbad|title=ACO 222|access-date=24 November 2017}}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-12|58|45}}<ref name=SIMBAD/> | brightest_member = LEDA 944643<ref>{{cite simbad|title=2MASX J01373406-1259288|access-date=24 November 2017}}</ref> | member_no = | richness = 3<ref name=ACO>{{cite journal|last1=Abell|first1=George O.|last2=Corwin|first2=Harold G., Jr.|last3=Olowin|first3=Ronald P.|date=May 1989|title=A catalog of rich clusters of galaxies|journal=Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series|volume=70|issue=May 1989|pages=1–138|format=PDF|issn=0067-0049|bibcode=1989ApJS...70....1A|doi=10.1086/191333}}</ref> | bmtype = II-III<ref name=ACO/> | h_radial_v = >30000 km/s | velocity_dispersion = 1014 km/s<ref name=Durret/> | redshift = 0.2110<ref name=ned>{{cite web|url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?objname=Abell+222&extend=no&out_csys=Equatorial&out_equinox=J2000.0&obj_sort=RA+or+Longitude&of=pre_text&zv_breaker=30000.0&list_limit=5&img_stamp=YES|title=NED results for object ABELL 0222|publisher=[[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] / [[Infrared Processing and Analysis Center]]|accessdate=24 November 2017}}</ref> | distance = {{convert|2.4|Mly|Mpc|abbr=on|lk=on}}<ref name=csmonitor/> | temperature = 3.77 ± 0.15 keV<ref name=Durret>{{cite journal|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201014566|title=The clusters Abell 222 and Abell 223: A multi-wavelength view|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=517|pages=A94|year=2010|last1=Durret|first1=F|last2=Laganá|first2=T. F|last3=Adami|first3=C|last4=Bertin|first4=E|bibcode=2010A&A...517A..94D|arxiv=1005.3295}}</ref><!-- kT --> | mass = <!-- 0{{e|14}} {{hub|0.00}} In solar masses --> | luminosity = | flux = | other_names = RXC J0137.4-1259<ref name=SIMBAD/> }} '''Abell 222''' is a [[galaxy cluster]] in the [[constellation]] of [[Cetus]]. It holds thousands of [[galaxies]] together. It is located at a distance of 2.4 billion light-years from [[Earth]].<ref name=csmonitor>{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2012/0705/Cosmic-scaffolding-uncovered-Scientists-find-thread-of-dark-matter |title=Cosmic scaffolding uncovered? Scientists find thread of dark matter. |author=Pete Spotts |date=5 July 2012|accessdate= 14 July 2012|work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|publisher=[[Christian Science Publishing Society]]}}</ref>
==Discovery of dark matter== Astronomers noticed an invisible string of matter was warping [[spacetime]] between Abell 222 and [[Abell 223]]. Upon further examination by using images from the Japanese Subaru telescope, astronomers discovered that this "invisible matter" is in fact [[dark matter]]. The astronomers used [[gravitational lens]]ing to detect the dark matter filaments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.science20.com/news_articles/dark_matter_filaments_detected_abell_222_and_abel_223_supercluster-91809|title=Dark Matter Filaments Detected In Abell 222 And Abel 223 Supercluster|date=2014-08-27|website=Science 2.0|language=en|access-date=2017-10-16}}</ref> The cluster is connected by a filament of dark matter to [[Abell 223]] that is permeated by hot X-ray emitting gas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esa.int/esa-mmg/mmg.pl?idf=SEMHZOZXUFF&type=I|title=ID: SEMHZOZXUFF: Galaxy clusters Abell 222 and Abell 223|publisher=esa|accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref> Further research shows that this filament only contains about 20 percent of normal matter, the rest is assumed to be dark matter. This is seen to be in good agreement with the [[Physical cosmology|cosmological standard model]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nzz.ch | title = Eine Brücke aus dunkler Materie zwischen zwei Galaxienhaufen | date = 17 July 2012 | language = German | publisher = Neue Zürcher Zeitung | archiveurl = http://www.nzz.ch/wissen/wissenschaft/eine-bruecke-aus-dunkler-materie-zwischen-zwei-galaxienhaufen-1.17367017 | archivedate = 17 July 2012 | accessdate = 2012-09-24 }}</ref>
==Baryonic matter== {{main|Baryon}} 5% of the universe is made up of baryonic or ordinary matter which contains protons and neutrons, also known as baryons, and electrons. Baryons and electrons are the foundation for atoms. Astronomers have not been able to locate the full 5% of baryonic matter within other galaxies, stars or gases. After observing gas that connects Abell 222 and Abell 223, scientists believe that the missing baryonic matter is within the gas that bridges the two galaxy clusters. This was difficult to locate due to the fact that the gas had a very low density, which made it hard to detect. This discovery was made possible because of Abell 222’s location. It is within Earth’s line of sight, so scientists were able to see a strong concentration of this gas within a section of the sky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.science20.com/news_releases/do_abell_222_and_abell_223_contain_the_universes_missing_baryonic_matter|title=Do Abell 222 And Abell 223 Contain The Universe's 'Missing' Baryonic Matter?|date=2014-08-27|website=Science 2.0|language=en|access-date=2017-10-16}}</ref>
