{{BLP sources|date=July 2013}}

'''Angela Milner''' is a British [[Paleontology|paleontologist]] who, in 1986, described a new species of ''[[Baryonyx]]''. Milner, who has a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norman |first1=David |last2=Milner |first2=Angela |date=August 2004 |title=Dinosaur - Eyewitness Books |url= |location= |publisher=DK Publishing |page=3 |isbn=0-7566-0647-0}}</ref> currently works at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London, where she continues her study on [[theropoda]] such as ''[[Darwinius|Darwinius masillae]]'', otherwise known as '''Ida'''. She also studied the brain work of ''[[Archaeopteryx]]'', which proved that the species was a bird. She also studies bird species from the [[Eocene]] period which are found in the southern [[England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/nature-online/life/dinosaurs-other-extinct-creatures/darwinius-masillae/angela-milner-on-ida/ |title=Angela Milner discusses the fossil record |publisher=Natural History Museum |accessdate=July 18, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504041205/http://www.nhm.ac.uk/nature-online/life/dinosaurs-other-extinct-creatures/darwinius-masillae/angela-milner-on-ida/ |archivedate=May 4, 2014 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>

