{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}
{{for|the stone frigate called ''HMS'' Euroclydon|Fort Verdala}} '''Euroclydon''' (or in Latin: '''Euroaquilo''') is a cyclonic tempestuous northeast wind which blows in the [[Mediterranean]], mostly in autumn and winter. It is the modern Gregalia ([[Gregale]]) or [[Viento de Levante|Levanter]]. From the Greek word ''eurokludōn'' [εὐροκλύδων], from ''Euros'' (Eurus, meaning east wind) and either the Greek word ''akulōn'' (akylōn, meaning north wind), or ''kludon'' (meaning a surging wave from the verb ''kluzo'' meaning to billow) or the Latin word ''aquilō'' (aquilon).
== Notable references == * In [[Acts 27|chapter 27]] in the [[Book of Acts]] 27:14 it may specifically refer to the name of the [[Gregale]] wind from the Adriatic Gulf, which wrecked the [[Paul of Tarsus|apostle Paul's]] ship on the coast of [[Malta]] on his way to Rome.<ref>"But not long after there arose against it a tempestuous wind, called Euroclydon." {{bibleverse||Acts|27:14|KJV}}</ref> * It is referenced in the second chapter of ''[[Moby-Dick]]''. *''Euroclydon'' is also the name of an anthem by [[William Billings]] *Referenced in "The Roman Centurion's Song" by [[Rudyard Kipling]]: "Here where our stiff-necked British oaks confront Euroclydon!" *Referenced in [[Dorothy L. Sayers]]' novel ''[[The Nine Tailors]]'' <ref>{{cite book |last=Sayers |first=Dorothy L |date=1934|edition=1948 |title=The Nine Tailors |location=London |publisher=Victor Gollancz |page=226}}</ref> where after a rainstorm, the Rector uses [http://www.sacred-texts.com/bib/kjv/act027.htm#014 the phrase from Acts 27:14]
